The Central Bank of Nigeria (CBN) has suspended foreign exchange (forex) sales to the Bureau De Change (BDC) operators until further notice. The Association of Bureau the Change of Nigeria (ABCON) had on the 24th of March written to the apex bank recommending a halt in the weekly sales of forex to BDCs The CBN in its response letter dated March 25, 2020, notified the operators of it decision to suspend sales. The letter states that the suspension follows the government’s directive to restrict gatherings to not more than 20 persons as a means of reducing person-to-person contact and curb the transmission of the Covid-19. However, a management source, who spoke to Daily Trust on condition of anonymity, said the action became necessary   given the sharp drop in demand for dollars, caused by the impact of the coronavirus on global trade and travels. “There is no pressure in the forex market, especially from the sectors serviced by the BDCs to warrant continued sales of exchange rate”, he said.  COVID-19: CBN suspends Forex sales to BDCs BDCs appeal to CBN for increased forex sale Will CBN finally stop sale  of Forex to BDCs in 2016?